WEBVTT

00:00.130 --> 00:02.694
Good morning and give it up for the Brown family.

00:09.886 --> 00:10.567
They were awesome.

00:13.852 --> 00:14.553
Oh, man.

00:17.518 --> 00:18.239
Well, good morning.

00:20.623 --> 00:24.850
We are continuing on in our message series called The Generous Life.

00:25.634 --> 00:31.003
I'm Tim, if you don't know me and I don't know you, I'm glad to get to see you and I hope to get to talk to you today.

00:33.066 --> 00:38.395
You know, I was thinking as I was preparing this message that there are certain things in my life that helped me feel anchored.

00:38.435 --> 00:42.322
For me, a lot of us tied to where I'm from.

00:42.362 --> 00:44.485
I'm sure you've all heard me.

00:44.565 --> 00:45.888
I'm from Cincinnati before.

00:45.908 --> 00:52.178
I'm literally wearing Cincinnati bangles socks right now, even though they're not in the playoffs.

00:54.210 --> 00:55.552
That's right, they're not in the playoffs.

00:57.454 --> 00:58.875
The playoffs are still fun to watch.

00:59.676 --> 01:16.876
Yeah, my home city, my family, the teams I grew up cheering for, the places that feel familiar, greater ice cream, I can just reel off everything that makes me feel connected, that makes me feel grounded, that makes me feel steady.

01:18.458 --> 01:21.842
When we were back home visiting Cincinnati,

01:22.306 --> 01:35.888
I remember the familiar roads and I felt at home, and I'm noticing slowly over three and a half years that when we come back, I feel at home too, which is a good feeling.

01:35.908 --> 01:41.336
When I see your faces, I'll even admit to you, I'm rooting for IU right now.

01:41.356 --> 01:49.810
I know that there's always the Purdue IU rivalry thing here, but I have to admit that selfishly speaking

01:50.178 --> 02:03.697
I'm enjoying that excitement and feeling of people excited for their team to win that I got to feel when I was on my way here when my team was making a fun run in the postseason.

02:03.737 --> 02:07.703
So go IU tomorrow night, even if it just makes me feel a little bit at home.

02:08.444 --> 02:18.418
And I've learned over time that when something makes me feel grounded, I start to hold on to it tighter than I realize.

02:19.906 --> 02:21.028
Anybody else like that?

02:23.411 --> 02:28.318
And it's not because it's bad to hold on to the things that make you feel grounded, that make you feel at home.

02:29.840 --> 02:36.790
But what happens is it starts doing a work in my heart that only God is meant to do.

02:39.453 --> 02:42.197
And that's not just true with places or people.

02:43.179 --> 02:48.466
It could be true with your work, with your own sense of self-control, with your routines,

02:48.930 --> 02:53.636
Even good things like doing ministry or being responsible.

02:54.878 --> 02:59.023
These things you can hold on so tightly to.

03:01.246 --> 03:02.248
And here's what I've noticed.

03:03.329 --> 03:06.033
I don't usually discover what I treasure by what I say.

03:07.234 --> 03:10.759
Just because I say I treasure something doesn't make it true.

03:10.779 --> 03:13.863
I discover what I treasure by what I protect.

03:14.784 --> 03:16.146
What I hold on tightly to.

03:17.314 --> 03:23.002
by what I prioritize, but what I feel anxious about losing.

03:25.126 --> 03:29.632
And Jesus would say that that's not accidental, that we feel that way about things.

03:30.734 --> 03:31.756
It's diagnostic.

03:33.418 --> 03:44.114
I mean, honestly, if we're, anybody ever realize that you can't find your phone, what do you do?

03:45.410 --> 03:47.832
You turn over the entire house to find it.

03:48.733 --> 03:53.638
You can't do the next thing on your plan or go to the next place until you have found it.

03:55.921 --> 04:02.828
That's what it feels like to feel unsettled when you lose control of something that you value that you want to protect.

04:04.670 --> 04:12.818
And that's why Jesus' words in Matthew six, which is one of the two passes we're gonna look at today, are so clarifying and yet so unsettling.

04:14.402 --> 04:18.386
He doesn't start the passage that we're looking at talking about money.

04:19.488 --> 04:23.612
I know the moment that we see the word generous in church, that's where our heads go.

04:24.533 --> 04:25.394
And that is a part of it.

04:26.956 --> 04:35.405
But what Jesus actually talks about is treasure, about what captures our affection, about what quietly shapes our hearts.

04:37.327 --> 04:40.550
And then he says something simple, but searching.

04:42.112 --> 04:43.794
He says, where your treasure is,

04:44.642 --> 04:47.606
There your heart will be also.

04:50.089 --> 04:52.893
Jesus isn't accusing anybody in this passage.

04:54.195 --> 04:56.839
He's revealing something true about all of us.

04:58.000 --> 05:07.653
He's saying, if you want to know what's forming your heart, look at what you're holding on tightly to.

05:10.277 --> 05:14.002
And that's exactly what he exposes gently, but honestly,

05:14.626 --> 05:22.658
in the story of the widow that most people overlooked, which is in Luke 21, which we're going to look at after Matthew 6.

05:24.040 --> 05:28.887
So I want to start with Matthew 6 this morning, and I want us to listen to Jesus carefully today.

05:28.927 --> 05:39.602
Not as someone trying to take something from us, but as a Savior trying to tell us the truth about what's already shaping us.

05:40.930 --> 05:46.377
So please open your Bibles or fall on the screens as we read Matthew 6, 19 through 24.

05:48.459 --> 05:59.273
Jesus says, don't store up for yourselves treasures on earth or moth and rust destroy and where thieves break in and steal.

06:00.274 --> 06:03.818
But store up for yourselves treasures in heaven.

06:04.559 --> 06:10.066
We're neither moth nor rust destroys and where thieves don't break in

06:10.274 --> 06:10.895
and steel.

06:11.696 --> 06:15.681
For where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.

06:16.642 --> 06:18.825
The eye is the lamp of the body.

06:19.406 --> 06:22.830
If your eye is healthy, your whole body will be full of light.

06:24.332 --> 06:27.896
But if your eye is bad, your whole body will be full of darkness.

06:28.697 --> 06:33.563
So if the light within you is darkness, how deep is that darkness?

06:34.284 --> 06:38.770
No one can serve two masters, since either he will hate one

06:39.522 --> 06:44.351
and love the other, or you will be devoted to one and despise the other.

06:45.654 --> 06:50.183
You cannot serve both God and money.

06:52.527 --> 07:02.226
And when Jesus says, do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth, he's not just doling out abstract spiritual advice.

07:03.010 --> 07:11.483
He was naming a reality that everyone in his world and in our world already understands, and they understood it deeply at the time that Jesus was speaking.

07:12.224 --> 07:15.408
In the ancient Mediterranean world, wealth was fragile.

07:16.850 --> 07:22.278
They were the haves, and they were a small percentage of the people, and then they were the have-nots, which were everybody else.

07:23.240 --> 07:26.805
And those people were trying to eke out a living, trying to scrape by daily.

07:28.247 --> 07:30.130
When Jesus and another

07:30.370 --> 07:39.420
And since teaches his disciples to pray, to pray that the Father will give them their daily bread, that wasn't just a nicety prayer.

07:39.460 --> 07:44.967
That was people praying who didn't know where their next meal would come from.

07:47.189 --> 07:49.732
What you had was fragile and could be lost.

07:50.493 --> 07:53.837
Treasure could be stolen, corrupted, or lost overnight.

07:54.197 --> 07:55.879
Moss destroyed clothes.

07:56.540 --> 07:58.162
Rust consumed metal.

07:58.274 --> 08:02.038
thieves broke into homes made out of mud and brick.

08:04.821 --> 08:11.509
So Jesus isn't exaggerating when he says this bit about treasures on earth.

08:12.430 --> 08:16.635
He's describing normal life that his hears would have experienced every day.

08:18.116 --> 08:26.706
So when Jesus contrasts treasures on earth with treasures in heaven, he's not contrasting bad things with good things,

08:27.106 --> 08:32.453
He's contrasting temporary security with ultimate security.

08:34.615 --> 08:37.178
And then he makes a statement that reframes everything.

08:39.081 --> 08:42.024
He says, where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.

08:42.986 --> 08:46.550
And I want us to clue into the direction that Jesus gives here.

08:46.870 --> 08:51.035
He doesn't say where your heart is, your treasure will follow.

08:52.037 --> 08:53.138
He says the opposite.

08:54.466 --> 08:59.512
In other words, Jesus teaches us that what we do with our resources trains our hearts.

09:00.113 --> 09:05.120
Treasure is not the reward of love, it is the revealer of love.

09:07.322 --> 09:22.642
Our spending, saving, giving habits, what we invest in, what we talk about most, what we care about most, expose what we trust, what we fear, and what we believe will carry us through life.

09:23.970 --> 09:27.176
And that's why Jesus immediately moves to the image of the eye.

09:27.977 --> 09:30.161
He says, the eye is the lamp of the body.

09:31.443 --> 09:40.218
And in Jesus' culture at the time of the Jewish people in the first century, the eye was understood as the organ of desire and focus.

09:41.180 --> 09:44.906
A healthier or clear eye didn't just mean good eyesight.

09:46.068 --> 09:49.554
It meant a generous eye, an undivided gaze.

09:50.178 --> 09:54.202
A bad eye instead referred to greed, envy, and stinginess.

09:55.783 --> 10:01.349
So Jesus is saying what you keep your eye on eventually determines what you live for.

10:03.891 --> 10:07.174
Follow your focus to see what you care most about.

10:08.916 --> 10:15.662
So this point is this, if your vision of life is shaped by trust in God, your whole life will be filled with light.

10:16.763 --> 10:19.986
But if your vision is shaped by anxiety and accumulation,

10:20.194 --> 10:21.536
Everything else darkens.

10:23.438 --> 10:30.148
And then Jesus delivers a line that's gonna tie Matthew 6 to the story we'll get to in a moment in Luke 21.

10:30.628 --> 10:32.631
He says, no one can serve two masters.

10:33.412 --> 10:36.336
You cannot serve both God and money.

10:38.199 --> 10:40.362
This is a pretty profound reality.

10:40.402 --> 10:43.626
It's one that is kind of ancient and foreign to us.

10:44.968 --> 10:49.074
We like to talk about love and hate as feelings and emotions,

10:49.154 --> 10:54.942
When Jesus talks about love and hate in this situation, he's talking about a hierarchy of priority.

10:55.823 --> 10:58.226
And only one thing can fill the top spot.

11:00.289 --> 11:02.712
And that one thing that fills the top spot is what you love.

11:03.794 --> 11:10.543
And if only thing can occupy the loved and first position, then two things can occupy it.

11:11.865 --> 11:13.947
So you can't have equal love for God and money.

11:13.967 --> 11:15.990
You can't have equal priority for God and money.

11:16.130 --> 11:18.834
Only one can fill the top spot.

11:20.386 --> 11:22.148
Now what's Jesus not saying?

11:22.328 --> 11:24.170
Well, Jesus isn't saying money is evil.

11:25.871 --> 11:27.613
Money is not a moral thing.

11:27.653 --> 11:29.395
Having money is not evil.

11:31.096 --> 11:36.181
But what he is cautioning is the love of money.

11:37.663 --> 11:40.706
Because the love of money can give money power.

11:40.766 --> 11:49.554
It can give money the ability to demand allegiance, to compete for trust, and eventually

11:49.634 --> 11:54.502
to ask us to worship it and put it in first priority.

11:57.727 --> 12:08.765
And that's where the widow's offering in Luke 21 will become a lived example of this teaching from Jesus in Matthew 6, because Jesus doesn't leave this teaching in the abstract.

12:09.085 --> 12:11.369
He walks into the temple and then he watches.

12:13.592 --> 12:17.138
The rich give large sums, but they give from surplus.

12:17.730 --> 12:19.592
Their security remains intact.

12:19.993 --> 12:22.476
Their treasure stays rooted in what they possess.

12:23.056 --> 12:27.702
They're giving while visible does not rearrange with their dependence.

12:29.144 --> 12:32.888
But the widow, as we'll see, gives all that she had to live on.

12:34.450 --> 12:38.455
So in Matthew 6, her treasure is not stored on earth.

12:39.636 --> 12:40.938
Her heart is not divided.

12:41.779 --> 12:44.722
She is not hedging her bets between God and money.

12:45.218 --> 12:47.983
Her gift reveals where her trust already lies.

12:49.665 --> 12:51.609
That's what Jesus is about to observe.

12:51.649 --> 12:55.996
He's not praising recklessness, he's revealing lordship.

12:56.957 --> 12:59.862
And the widow's small coins expose a massive truth.

13:00.904 --> 13:04.470
The generosity is never about the amount, it's about allegiance.

13:05.291 --> 13:11.762
What matters is not how much is released, but who is being trusted with what you have.

13:12.386 --> 13:20.778
So when Jesus says what you treasure tells the truth about your heart, he's not condemning wealth or idealizing poverty.

13:21.799 --> 13:24.824
He's diagnosing discipleship.

13:26.346 --> 13:31.173
And that's why I want to give us our bottom line today before we get into the Luke 21 story.

13:31.754 --> 13:37.862
And that is that what we treasure most always tells the truth about our hearts.

13:38.984 --> 13:40.466
What we treasure most

13:40.578 --> 13:42.721
always tells the truth about our hearts.

13:43.302 --> 13:49.189
Treasures reveal masters, spending reveals trust, giving reveals worship.

13:49.570 --> 13:54.737
And what you treasure most will always shape who you become.

13:56.719 --> 14:01.466
So I want to look at this story of Jesus observing the poor widow in Luke 21.

14:02.427 --> 14:03.709
It's in verses one through four.

14:03.769 --> 14:04.850
You can follow along.

14:06.210 --> 14:10.897
says Jesus looked up and saw the rich dropping their offerings into the temple treasury.

14:11.959 --> 14:14.983
And he also saw poor widow dropping in two tiny coins.

14:16.005 --> 14:21.233
Truly I tell you, he said, this poor widow has put in more than all of them.

14:22.475 --> 14:32.370
For all these people have put in gifts out of their surplus, but she out of her poverty has put in all she had to live on.

14:34.306 --> 14:41.654
When Luke tells the story of the widow's offering, he wants his disciples to see something the culture around them would have missed.

14:43.556 --> 14:46.500
In Jesus' world, wealth didn't just mean that you had more money.

14:47.200 --> 14:49.223
Wealth automatically carried status.

14:51.305 --> 14:55.449
It placed you in the leadership and the ruling class.

14:56.671 --> 15:03.218
And that meant that when wealthy people gave publicly, they're giving tended to be read as both generous and admirable,

15:03.490 --> 15:08.736
because cultural assumptions already treated the rich as the important people.

15:10.938 --> 15:14.342
So I love the way that Luke is careful with his wording in this story.

15:15.663 --> 15:23.612
He tells us that Jesus observes that the rich put in large sums, but then he adds a detail that changes the way we evaluate the whole story.

15:24.453 --> 15:26.075
They gave out of their abundance.

15:27.757 --> 15:28.537
It didn't hurt.

15:28.577 --> 15:32.722
It didn't hurt them one bit to give.

15:34.882 --> 15:42.654
They gave out of what was left over, what was surplus for them, and what they could spare without any real cost to their daily life.

15:43.795 --> 15:55.573
Because much like or against what the common people, the 95% or more were living, they didn't have to worry about where their next meal was coming from.

15:58.617 --> 15:59.639
But the widow is different.

16:02.243 --> 16:04.466
Luke says that she gave out of her poverty.

16:05.282 --> 16:09.207
Not out of what she had extra, but out of what she lacked.

16:10.629 --> 16:14.955
She gave from what was insufficient even for her own support.

16:16.217 --> 16:19.381
What she had wouldn't have gone very far, but she gave it away anyway.

16:21.064 --> 16:23.006
Her gift was not an impressive amount.

16:23.747 --> 16:28.554
No one watching her would have been like, wow, I can't believe you're giving such a large gift.

16:30.296 --> 16:34.642
It was costly and proportion to what she had, and it demanded trust.

16:35.490 --> 16:37.552
And that's why Jesus slows the moment down.

16:38.694 --> 16:45.782
So his disciples don't miss what the world would have applauded and what God actually sees.

16:49.086 --> 16:57.816
It's important for us to pause for a moment and consider what Jesus notices and what we often miss.

17:00.119 --> 17:02.802
And this is where Jesus would have shocked his disciples.

17:04.258 --> 17:18.678
He tells his disciples that heard small gift, the gift that would have seemed insignificant to everybody else, is greater than what the others were putting in the plates.

17:21.241 --> 17:30.354
That idea that a poor person's small offering could be more meaningful than a rich person's large offering wasn't completely unheard of in the ancient world.

17:30.978 --> 17:40.111
There are some parallels in Greek and Jewish traditions, but Jesus' evaluation still is radical because it's impractical.

17:40.592 --> 17:44.657
If you think about her survival, it almost sounds irresponsible.

17:46.560 --> 17:47.281
And that's the point.

17:48.603 --> 17:52.008
Jesus isn't giving financial planning advice here.

17:54.732 --> 17:59.218
Jesus isn't interested in telling his disciples how to get rich.

18:01.474 --> 18:03.136
He's revealing what God values.

18:04.458 --> 18:06.460
And for Jesus, that's all that matters.

18:08.683 --> 18:12.048
In the kingdom of God, the value of the gift isn't measured by the number on it.

18:12.388 --> 18:14.371
It's measured by the heart behind it.

18:15.773 --> 18:22.962
The quality of the offering, trust, surrender, dependence matters more than the sum of the offering.

18:24.224 --> 18:26.667
And Luke is doing something else at the same time.

18:27.988 --> 18:29.170
See, in the ancient world,

18:29.442 --> 18:32.445
How someone used their possessions was not seen as private.

18:33.366 --> 18:36.269
Possessions function like a barometer of faithfulness.

18:37.170 --> 18:41.335
People measured commitment by what they did with what they had.

18:41.375 --> 18:45.979
And even more, economic sharing was tied to social belonging.

18:46.660 --> 18:53.327
To share without expecting anything in return was to treat someone as kin, as family.

18:54.388 --> 18:56.050
That's why when Jesus tells the

18:56.130 --> 19:13.006
rich ruler in another story to sell what he has and give it to the poor, he's not merely asking for charity, he's inviting a reordering of loyalty, relationships, and identity as one embodied by expression of devotion to God.

19:14.868 --> 19:18.071
And that's what Jesus catches in this story in Luke 21.

19:19.172 --> 19:21.654
Jesus isn't praising the widow because she's poor.

19:23.335 --> 19:26.098
He's praising her because her money

19:26.658 --> 19:27.679
is not her master.

19:29.761 --> 19:31.062
She is not serving money.

19:31.122 --> 19:33.565
Her treasure isn't in what she keeps.

19:34.266 --> 19:36.328
Her treasure is in God.

19:38.230 --> 19:41.313
And that connects directly to what Jesus teaches in Matthew 6.

19:42.714 --> 19:52.304
Jesus came to announce God's reversal of human standards, where worth is not measured by power, wealth, or visibility.

19:53.385 --> 19:54.706
In God's kingdom,

19:56.066 --> 19:58.649
And God's kingdom, the rich, aren't automatically the faithful.

19:59.210 --> 20:01.373
And the poor aren't automatically forgotten.

20:02.835 --> 20:04.938
God sees what others overlook.

20:05.719 --> 20:08.022
God honors what others dismiss.

20:09.164 --> 20:12.768
And so the widow's offering becomes a living picture of Jesus' point.

20:13.089 --> 20:15.152
The question isn't how much did she give.

20:15.192 --> 20:21.520
The question is, what did her giving reveal about what she treasured the most?

20:23.883 --> 20:25.906
Jesus' teaching here isn't about money.

20:26.370 --> 20:27.472
It's about direction.

20:29.175 --> 20:34.324
He's teaching us your life will move toward wherever and whatever you treasure.

20:35.106 --> 20:37.510
Your attention will drift toward it.

20:37.830 --> 20:40.796
Your energy will be shaped by it.

20:41.256 --> 20:47.548
Your decisions will orbit about it because treasure doesn't just sit somewhere.

20:48.229 --> 20:51.154
It pulls into its direction.

20:52.290 --> 20:54.713
And that's why Jesus doesn't say, don't have treasure.

20:54.753 --> 20:56.655
He says, be careful where you store it.

20:59.940 --> 21:02.663
Because where your treasure is, your heart will follow.

21:03.724 --> 21:06.528
And that's what the widow reveals in Luke 21.

21:07.129 --> 21:08.791
She doesn't give because she has to.

21:09.371 --> 21:12.155
She gives because something else matters more than holding on.

21:13.657 --> 21:20.946
Her small gift exposes a big truth, that what we value most shows up and what we protect

21:21.250 --> 21:26.695
in what we pursue and what we're willing to release and to let go of.

21:28.337 --> 21:32.080
And so we're invited not to feel guilty, but to look honestly.

21:32.140 --> 21:37.966
Not to audit our bank accounts, but to notice what's been quietly forming us.

21:38.587 --> 21:44.412
Not to ask how generous am I, but what it is that I value the most.

21:46.354 --> 21:50.418
Because generosity is always downstream

21:50.978 --> 21:51.579
from value.

21:53.060 --> 21:56.905
If I value security above all, I will store and protect.

21:57.946 --> 22:01.970
If I value comfort above all, I will spend and consume.

22:01.990 --> 22:08.217
If I value status above all, I will display and accumulate.

22:08.618 --> 22:13.603
And if I value God's kingdom above all, I will invest beyond myself.

22:15.785 --> 22:19.890
Jesus is asking us to notice what already has

22:20.514 --> 22:21.335
our affection.

22:23.138 --> 22:24.159
And this is detention.

22:25.481 --> 22:29.607
Most of us don't consciously choose our treasures.

22:30.909 --> 22:33.192
They slowly choose us.

22:36.317 --> 22:39.561
I talked at the beginning about, you know, I'm a Cincinnati guy.

22:39.581 --> 22:48.594
You think if you look at the record of the Cincinnati Bengals that I would have chose them myself, that's my mom's fault, okay?

22:49.378 --> 22:50.680
I was born into it.

22:51.721 --> 22:52.582
It's in my blood.

22:57.288 --> 22:59.411
That's why Jesus gives us this warning.

23:01.213 --> 23:03.096
You can't serve both God and money.

23:04.257 --> 23:10.365
Not because money is evil, but because it can be powerful, compete for attention, and shape imagination.

23:11.186 --> 23:17.554
Everything that we are pulled toward that chooses us competes for our time, our attention, and our devotion.

23:18.754 --> 23:20.416
It's not even just about money.

23:21.778 --> 23:24.141
It's about everything that pulls us in.

23:24.201 --> 23:33.051
And if we're honest and we take a look inside, we've all got something that pulls us in.

23:34.053 --> 23:34.653
I know I do.

23:36.335 --> 23:45.106
And Jesus loves us too much to let something temporary define something eternal.

23:47.426 --> 23:50.310
So what does it look like in everyday life?

23:51.031 --> 23:54.697
Well first, Jesus invites us to relocate our treasure.

23:55.898 --> 23:59.043
Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth, Jesus says.

24:00.265 --> 24:01.727
He's not saying don't plan.

24:01.787 --> 24:04.892
He's saying don't confuse planning with purpose.

24:05.953 --> 24:07.255
Earthly treasure wears out.

24:07.295 --> 24:07.936
It breaks.

24:08.357 --> 24:09.278
It depreciates.

24:09.599 --> 24:10.720
It gets left behind.

24:10.780 --> 24:12.243
You can't take it with you.

24:14.586 --> 24:17.330
Heavenly treasure lasts because it's invested in people.

24:17.666 --> 24:33.288
Faithfulness, obedience, love, generosity, and the work God is doing in the world for the sake of the kingdom, which means generosity isn't about losing something, it's about placing it somewhere better.

24:33.308 --> 24:37.614
Second, Jesus invites us to retrain our vision.

24:38.315 --> 24:40.498
He says, the eye is the lamp of the body.

24:41.026 --> 24:45.291
Jesus knows that what we look at long enough eventually shapes what we love.

24:45.731 --> 24:53.280
If our vision is fixed on what we own, what we lack, or what others have, our hearts become divided.

24:54.762 --> 25:03.752
But when our vision is fixed on God's kingdom, on what He is doing, on who He is forming us to become, our lives gain clarity.

25:04.973 --> 25:08.978
This is not about trying harder, it's about looking differently.

25:09.698 --> 25:12.903
And third, Jesus invites us to re-center our allegiance.

25:13.904 --> 25:16.949
He says, no one can serve two masters.

25:17.530 --> 25:18.591
This is not a threat.

25:19.232 --> 25:19.833
It's mercy.

25:20.915 --> 25:22.497
Jesus is naming reality.

25:22.998 --> 25:25.381
Something will always be at the center.

25:26.102 --> 25:28.967
Something will always set the agenda in our lives.

25:29.227 --> 25:34.194
And whatever sits at the center quietly shapes the choices that we make.

25:36.818 --> 25:39.442
So Jesus asks, who or what?

25:39.522 --> 25:41.424
is worthy of that place.

25:42.305 --> 25:44.989
And this is where the gospel speaks most clearly.

25:46.130 --> 25:51.377
Because before Jesus ever asks us to treasure him, he treasured us.

25:53.600 --> 26:03.252
At the cross, Jesus gave what he valued most, his life, not because we were generous, but because we were loved by him.

26:04.453 --> 26:08.338
He trusted the Father with everything so we wouldn't have to live

26:08.546 --> 26:16.916
clinging to temporary things, which means Christian generosity is not about proving our devotion to God.

26:16.956 --> 26:20.841
It's about responding to his devotion to us.

26:23.404 --> 26:26.148
We don't invest in God's kingdom to earn grace.

26:27.009 --> 26:30.793
We invest because grace has already found us.

26:32.295 --> 26:38.002
So here's a simple invitation of what Jesus is teaching and what he observes with this widow.

26:39.202 --> 26:46.330
Pay attention to what you value and let Jesus gently over time reshape it.

26:47.772 --> 26:52.477
Not all at once, not perfectly, but intentionally.

26:53.478 --> 26:57.243
Because what we treasure most will always tell the truth about our hearts.

26:58.644 --> 27:01.027
And Jesus isn't trying to take something from us.

27:01.868 --> 27:07.314
He's inviting us into a life where what matters most lasts forever.

27:10.178 --> 27:19.391
Now, one of the details in Luke's story about the poor widow that keeps getting my attention every time I read this story is this.

27:21.354 --> 27:22.716
Jesus notices her.

27:26.121 --> 27:27.743
That's the very first part of the story.

27:28.765 --> 27:38.098
Before he says his observation, before he pulls his disciples over, he simply notices this poor woman.

27:40.002 --> 27:44.608
Not from a distance, not accidentally, not as a teaching prop.

27:45.669 --> 27:57.123
He sees her in a crowded temple surrounded by larger gifts and more impressive people, more secure, more faithful on the surface people.

27:58.745 --> 28:00.948
Jesus sees her.

28:02.730 --> 28:04.392
He values her.

28:07.096 --> 28:08.818
And Jesus does not call her out.

28:09.474 --> 28:10.696
He doesn't embarrass her.

28:11.537 --> 28:14.520
He doesn't turn her story into a command for everyone else.

28:15.382 --> 28:22.631
I don't know if you noticed, but when you're reading the story, Jesus doesn't get up and teach everybody and say, everybody, look at this poor widow, look what she did.

28:22.671 --> 28:26.356
He teaches quietly to his disciples that are nearby.

28:26.416 --> 28:31.022
And he simply tells them the truth about what he sees.

28:32.443 --> 28:37.650
In her he sees trust, he sees love, and he sees a heart.

28:38.082 --> 28:44.612
that has placed its hopes somewhere deeper than anything this world can offer us.

28:46.855 --> 28:54.326
And what strikes me in this story is that Jesus doesn't just say she gave more because she was better than everybody else.

28:55.548 --> 29:01.557
He says she gave more because she gave herself.

29:01.577 --> 29:02.839
That's what treasure really is.

29:04.020 --> 29:05.503
Treasure isn't what we own.

29:05.563 --> 29:07.826
It's what owns us.

29:08.322 --> 29:10.764
It's what we cling to when life feels unstable.

29:11.345 --> 29:13.427
It's what we protect when we feel anxious.

29:14.188 --> 29:19.653
It's what we quietly, it's what quietly tells us, if I have this, I'll be okay.

29:21.034 --> 29:23.317
And Jesus doesn't expose that to shame us.

29:23.797 --> 29:25.639
He exposes it to heal us.

29:26.620 --> 29:28.402
Because he knows this to be true.

29:29.062 --> 29:31.825
Whatever holds our heart will eventually shape our life.

29:32.626 --> 29:36.850
And that's why Jesus says, where your treasure is, there your heart

29:37.122 --> 29:38.243
will be also.

29:38.304 --> 29:46.314
Not as a threat, not as pressure, but as an invitation to ask, what have I been asking to give me peace?

29:47.556 --> 29:49.899
What have I been asking to give me control?

29:49.939 --> 29:53.784
What have I been asking to make me feel safe?

29:55.466 --> 30:04.338
And then to place that trust where it actually belongs, at the cross Jesus gave what he treasured most his life for hours.

30:05.090 --> 30:11.677
He didn't give from excess, he didn't give what was convenient, he gave himself the whole thing.

30:13.379 --> 30:17.584
So when Jesus looks at us, he's not first asking, how much did you give?

30:17.644 --> 30:20.807
He's asking, where's your heart resting?

30:21.889 --> 30:29.097
And the good news is this, just like Jesus saw that woman in the temple, Jesus sees you and me.

30:30.258 --> 30:34.002
He knows us, and he invites us again and again

30:34.082 --> 30:41.310
to reorder our lives, not to keep up appearances, not to prove our faith, but to live free.

30:42.371 --> 30:48.038
Because when Christ becomes our treasure, everything else finds its proper place.

30:49.900 --> 30:54.565
Wherever you are right now, Jesus is not asking for a performance.

30:55.826 --> 30:58.409
He's inviting a reordering of love.

31:00.531 --> 31:02.834
None of the things that we count as treasure

31:03.394 --> 31:04.536
are inherently bad.

31:06.138 --> 31:19.337
But Jesus calls us to treasure him and the kingdom as first priority so that everything else finds its proper place in our lives.

31:19.658 --> 31:23.723
I hope that when he came in today, you got a communion packet.

31:28.410 --> 31:30.994
Jesus gave his life

31:32.066 --> 31:35.410
so that we could have life and have it to the full.

31:38.013 --> 31:40.517
He gave his life before we valued him.

31:40.717 --> 31:42.859
He gave his life while we were still sinners.

31:43.320 --> 31:48.386
He gave us his life while our priorities were still out of whack.

31:49.688 --> 31:53.112
He made the first move because he loves us.

31:55.095 --> 31:57.197
And he calls us to love him in response.

31:59.000 --> 32:00.882
And one of the ways that we show love

32:01.474 --> 32:12.210
to Jesus' to be obedient to him and on the night that he was betrayed, Jesus took bread and he broke it and he gave it to his disciples as they were gathered around the meal and he said, take this and eat.

32:12.290 --> 32:15.554
This is my body which is given for you.

32:15.574 --> 32:21.503
And in the same way he had them pass a cup and he said, take this and drink.

32:22.004 --> 32:24.227
This is my blood which is poured out for you.

32:24.267 --> 32:29.074
And then he said to them, he said, do this in remembrance of me.

32:29.666 --> 32:31.448
That's the command, do this.

32:33.871 --> 32:43.602
Every time we take communion, it's one step each Sunday where Jesus is working on each and every one of us to reorient our lives toward Him.

32:43.662 --> 32:52.251
Because it's a moment where we can be obedient and to say, I trust you with my life because you gave yours first.

32:54.454 --> 32:58.418
What good news it is that Jesus gave us His life.

32:59.522 --> 33:02.410
that God showed us mercy and grace through His Son.

33:04.215 --> 33:09.952
So I'm gonna give us a moment right now to pause and reflect on God's goodness, His grace, His mercy.

33:09.992 --> 33:15.026
And after that moment of reflection, we'll take communion together as one church family.

34:06.754 --> 34:13.884
each and every one of you to take the bread and eat, this is his body which is given for us.

34:20.974 --> 34:26.642
And likewise, I invite you to take and drink from this cup, this is his blood which is poured out.

34:36.482 --> 34:37.283
Please pray with me.

34:40.006 --> 34:43.390
Dear Lord God, we thank You for this morning.

34:45.293 --> 34:58.188
We thank You that while You call us to be generous, we know that You took the first step.

35:00.351 --> 35:06.098
You ask us to respond to what You've already done and what You've already done is more than enough.

35:08.418 --> 35:24.401
And I pray, Lord, that as we contemplate the high bar that you set for our lives, that through your grace and mercy, you do not leave us to our own devices to jump high and reach it.

35:26.443 --> 35:36.818
But that through your grace and the power of your spirit, you help to reshape us and reorient us day by day while we

35:37.250 --> 35:38.832
Make mistake after mistake.

35:39.553 --> 35:45.641
You don't give up on us, but you pick us back up and keep us going along on that journey.

35:47.223 --> 36:05.746
Pray that you'll continue to mold each and every one of us into your disciples so that we'll glorify you with our lives and so that we'll be light to the world around us, that we will look to others and see their value through your eyes

36:07.362 --> 36:14.131
See the way that your kingdom desires to shape this world, to save it, to rescue it.

36:17.695 --> 36:25.786
We thank you so much for being good to us, for working through us, and for helping us along the way.

36:25.826 --> 36:27.468
And it's in your son, Jesus, the same way, pray.

36:28.750 --> 36:28.850
Amen.

